{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2013}} {{Italic title}} {{Infobox court case |name = Hamed & Ors v. R |court = [[Supreme Court of New Zealand]] |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = |date decided = {{start date|2011|09|02|df=y}} |citations = [2011] NZSC 101 |ECLI = |transcripts = |judges = [[Sian Elias|Elias]] CJ, [[Peter Blanchard|Blanchard]], [[Andrew Tipping|Tipping]], [[John McGrath (judge)|McGrath]] and [[Thomas Gault|Gault]] JJ |number of judges = |decision by = |concurring = |dissenting = |concur/dissent = |prior actions = |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = <!-- {{hlist | }} --> |italic title = }} '''''Hamed & Ors v. R''''' [2011] NZSC 101<ref>https://www.courtsofnz.govt.nz/cases/hamed-v-r/ Hamed and others v The Queen [2011] NZSC 101</ref> was a decision by the [[Supreme Court of New Zealand]] which ruled on the admissibility of video surveillance. The ruling held that evidence collected using criminal trespass on private land to conduct covert surveillance under a warrant is only admissible for serious crimes. The charges involved were related to the [[2007 New Zealand anti-terror raids]], as a result of the ruling, charges against all but four of the defendants were dropped.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/5701220/Molotov-cocktail-talk-in-Urewera-court-files |title= Molotov cocktail talk in Urewera court files |author=Ian Steward |work=Stuff/Fairfax |date=29 September 2011 |quote=A raft of pre-trial judgments have been released following the discharge of 13 of the original Urewera 17, who were arrested following police surveillance of military-style training camps in the Urewera Ranges in 2007. |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/5638206/Police-made-repeated-trips-to-Urewera-camps |title=Police Made Numerous Trips to Urewera 'camps' |work=The Dominion Post |author=Fairfax NZ News |date=16 September 2011 |quote=They continued the secret filming long after it became obvious that the violent seizure of land that was feared was not in immediate prospect, a Supreme Court judgement that is now able to be published says. |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>
The ruling was initially suppressed from 24 March 2011 to September 2011. Very shortly after the lifting of the suppression, the [[Video Camera Surveillance (Temporary Measures) Act 2011]]<ref name=parl>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/PB/Legislation/Bills/1/b/f/00DBHOH_BILL11056_1-Video-Camera-Surveillance-Temporary-Measures-Bill.htm |title=Video Camera Surveillance (Temporary Measures) Bill |publisher=Parliament of New Zealand |accessdate=2011-10-03}}</ref> was introduced and passed under urgency.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10753400 |title=Urewera case five reasons to worry |author=Mai Chen |work=New Zealand Herald |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>
