{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Our Dumb World: The Onion's Atlas of the Planet Earth | translator = | image = Our Dumb World.jpg | caption = First edition cover | author = [[The Onion]] | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Satire]] | published = 30 October 2007 ([[Little, Brown and Company]]) | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]]) | pages = 245 | isbn = 978-0316018425 | oclc = 474118895 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Our Dumb World''''' is a parody of the standard desk [[atlas]] created by the staff of ''[[The Onion]]'' and published by [[Little, Brown and Company]] on October 30, 2007. It is The Onion's first book of entirely original content since 1999's ''[[Our Dumb Century]]''.
The book, written in the satirical paper's editorial voice, contains entries for nearly every country on [[Earth]], including detailed maps, feature articles, and humorous stereotyped descriptions of regional history and customs. For example, [[Romania|Romania's]] entry is subtitled, "[[Bram Stoker]]'s Romania."
There are eight distinct sections of the atlas. In order, [[North America]], [[South America]], [[Africa]], [[Middle East]], [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Oceania]], and Extra. Included in the Extra section are the Northern and Southern Poles and [[Greenland]], which is "[[Mercator projection|larger than Africa and South America combined.]]"
The visual style of the book has been compared to [[Dorling Kindersley]]'s [[Eyewitness Books|Eyewitness]] series.<ref>Cary Darling. "[http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-0103reader_jan03,0,304285.story Onion's 'Our Dumb World' could pass for what it's mocking]". ''Chicago Tribune''. January 3, 2008. 5.</ref> The book uses faux [[xenophobia]] to illustrate the cultural differences of various nations, often mocking racial stereotypes with satirical comments. Each section contains "facts" about the nation, a brief history, and other information.
Elements of the book have been transferred to an electronic format available on the paper's website and as a layer on [[Google Earth]]. ''Our Dumb World'' is also available as an audio book. __NOTOC__ ==Critical reaction== Critical reaction to "Our Dumb World" has been generally positive with reviewers praising the humor and use of satire.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones |first=Malcolm |url=http://www.newsweek.com/2007/10/30/the-onion-puts-its-spin-on-the-globe.html |title=The Onion’s Excellent ‘Atlas’ |publisher=Newsweek |date=2007-10-30 |accessdate=2013-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17548016 |title='Dumb World' is Vivid, Enthralling Misinformation |publisher=NPR |date=December 22, 2007 |accessdate=2013-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson |first=Margaret |url=http://www.denverpost.com/allewis/ci_7535581 |title=The Onion has unreal appeal |publisher=The Denver Post |date=2012-05-26 |accessdate=2013-12-07}}</ref> In the ''New York Times'', William Grimes called it "an astoundingly offensive guide to the states of the union and the countries of the world, compiled on the premise that all countries are ridiculous and contemptible" and found it "sophomoric, transgressive and intermittently brilliant."<ref>William Grimes, "[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/23/books/23maps.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 From the Glove Compartment to the Shelf.]" ''New York Times''. Nov. 23, 2007</ref>
